**17. Hub**

## Definition

A **Hub** is a basic networking device that connects multiple devices in a Local Area Network (LAN). It does not understand the destination of the data. Instead, it simply copies incoming data to every connected device.

---

## Working

Suppose we have:

```
          Hub
        /  |  \
 Laptop Phone TV
```

The Laptop sends data to the Phone.

The Hub does this:

```
Laptop
   │
   ▼
Hub
├────► Phone
├────► TV
└────► Printer
```

Every connected device receives the packet, even though only the Phone needs it.

---

## Characteristics

- Very simple device
- No intelligence
- Does not store addresses
- Broadcasts every frame
- Causes unnecessary network traffic

---

## Advantages

- Cheap
- Easy to install
- No configuration required

---

## Disadvantages

- Slow
- Wastes bandwidth
- Poor security
- High chance of collisions

---

# **18. Switch**

## Definition

A **Switch** is a networking device that connects devices in a LAN and intelligently forwards data only to the intended destination.

Unlike a Hub, a Switch learns the MAC addresses of connected devices.

---

## Working

```
          Switch
         /   |   \
 Laptop Phone TV
```

Laptop sends data to Phone.

The Switch checks its MAC Address Table.

```
Laptop
   │
   ▼
Switch
   │
   ▼
Phone
```

Only the Phone receives the frame.

---

## Advantages

- Faster than Hub
- Better bandwidth utilization
- More secure
- Reduces collisions
- Learns device locations automatically

---

# **19. MAC Address Table (CAM Table)**

## Definition

A Switch maintains a **MAC Address Table** (also called a CAM Table) that maps MAC addresses to switch ports.

Example:

|MAC Address|Port|
|---|---|
|AA:AA:AA|1|
|BB:BB:BB|2|
|CC:CC:CC|3|

Whenever a frame arrives, the switch checks this table and forwards the frame only to the correct port.

---

## How the Switch Learns

The switch automatically learns MAC addresses by observing the **source MAC address** of incoming frames.

No manual configuration is required.

---

# **20. Broadcast**

## Definition

A **Broadcast** is a packet that is sent to **every device** on the local network.

Example:

```
Who has 192.168.1.10?
```

Every device receives the request.

Only the device with that IP responds.

---

## Examples of Broadcast

- ARP Request
- DHCP Discover

---

## Advantages

- Finds unknown devices
- Simple communication

---

## Disadvantages

- Creates unnecessary traffic
- Reduces performance if excessive

---

# **21. Collision**

## Definition

A **Collision** occurs when two devices transmit data at exactly the same time on the same communication medium.

Example:

```
Laptop ──►
          X
Phone ───►
```

Both packets collide and become corrupted.

---

## Why Hubs Cause More Collisions

Since a Hub sends traffic to everyone, multiple devices may try to transmit simultaneously, increasing collisions.

Switches reduce collisions because they create separate communication paths.

---

# **22. OSI Model**

## Definition

The **OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model** is a conceptual framework that explains how data travels from one device to another through seven layers.

Each layer performs a specific task.

---

## The Seven Layers

|Layer|Name|Main Function|
|---|---|---|
|7|Application|User interaction|
|6|Presentation|Encryption, Compression|
|5|Session|Manages communication sessions|
|4|Transport|Reliable delivery (TCP/UDP)|
|3|Network|IP Addressing & Routing|
|2|Data Link|MAC Address & Switching|
|1|Physical|Transmission of Bits|

---

# **23. Layer 1 – Physical Layer**

### Responsibilities

- Sends Bits
- Uses cables or wireless signals
- Does not understand IP or MAC addresses

Examples:

- Ethernet Cable
- Fiber Optic
- Wi-Fi Signals

---

# **24. Layer 2 – Data Link Layer**

### Responsibilities

- MAC Addressing
- Frames
- Switches
- ARP

Devices:

- Switch

Protocols:

- Ethernet
- ARP

---

# **25. Layer 3 – Network Layer**

### Responsibilities

- IP Addressing
- Routing
- Packet Forwarding

Devices:

- Router

Protocols:

- IP
- ICMP

---

# **26. Layer 4 – Transport Layer**

### Responsibilities

- Reliability
- Error Detection
- Packet Ordering
- Port Numbers

Protocols:

- TCP
- UDP

---

# **27. Layer 5 – Session Layer**

### Responsibilities

- Establishes communication sessions
- Maintains communication
- Terminates sessions

---

# **28. Layer 6 – Presentation Layer**

### Responsibilities

- Encryption
- Compression
- Data Formatting

Example:

HTTPS encryption is handled here conceptually.

---

# **29. Layer 7 – Application Layer**

### Responsibilities

- Interface between user and network

Examples:

- Chrome
- Firefox
- WhatsApp
- Gmail

---

# **30. Encapsulation**

## Definition

Encapsulation is the process of **adding headers (and at Layer 2, a trailer)** to data as it moves down the OSI layers before transmission.

---

## Data Transformation

```
Application
      │
      ▼
Data
      │
Transport
      ▼
Segment
      │
Network
      ▼
Packet
      │
Data Link
      ▼
Frame
      │
Physical
      ▼
Bits
```

Each layer adds information required for its specific task.

---

# **31. Decapsulation**

## Definition

Decapsulation is the reverse process of encapsulation.

As data reaches the receiver, each layer removes its own header and passes the remaining data to the next layer.

---

## Process

```
Bits
 │
 ▼
Frame
 │
 ▼
Packet
 │
 ▼
Segment
 │
 ▼
Data
```

---

# **32. Layer Responsibilities Summary**

|Layer|Adds|
|---|---|
|Application|Data|
|Transport|Source & Destination Ports|
|Network|Source & Destination IP|
|Data Link|Source & Destination MAC|
|Physical|Converts into Bits|

---

# **33. Important Differences**

## Hub vs Switch

|Hub|Switch|
|---|---|
|Broadcasts to all devices|Sends only to destination|
|No intelligence|Learns MAC addresses|
|Slow|Fast|
|High collisions|Very few collisions|
|Rarely used today|Used everywhere|

---

## MAC Address vs IP Address

|MAC Address|IP Address|
|---|---|
|Physical Address|Logical Address|
|Layer 2|Layer 3|
|Used within LAN|Used across networks|
|Usually permanent|Can change|

---

## Switch vs Router

|Switch|Router|
|---|---|
|Uses MAC Address|Uses IP Address|
|Layer 2|Layer 3|
|Connects devices in LAN|Connects different networks|

---

